nt%20of%20overseas%20workers%20to%20Israel%2C%20which%20began%20as%20early%20as%20the%201970s%2C%20followed%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.law.uchicago.edu%2Fbilateral-labor-agreements-dataset%5C%22%3Epost-World%20War%20II%20trend%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20saw%20higher-income%20countries%20%E2%80%93%20such%20as%20the%20U.S.%2C%20France%20and%20West%20Germany%20%E2%80%93%20sign%20labor%20migration%20recruitment%20agreements%20with%20poorer%20nations.%20These%20poorer%20countries%2C%20which%20at%20the%20time%20included%20Mexico%2C%20Spain%20and%20Turkey%2C%20among%20others%2C%20overcame%20an%20initial%20reluctance%20to%20lose%20part%20of%20their%20populace%20and%20began%20to%20see%20emigration%20as%20a%20strategy%20for%20modernization.%20The%20idea%20was%20that%20emigrants%20could%20learn%20modern%20farming%20or%20industrial%20skills%20overseas%2C%20while%20sending%20money%20back%20to%20boost%20development%20in%20their%20home%20communities.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%201970s%20and%201980s%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.upress.umn.edu%2Fbook-division%2Fbooks%2Fmigrants-for-export%5C%22%3Emany%20South%20and%20Southeast%20Asian%20countries%3C%2Fa%3E%20began%20to%20promote%20the%20export%20of%20migrant%20workers%20as%20a%20key%20piece%20of%20their%20economic%20development%20strategies.%20At%20the%20same%20time%2C%20receiving%20countries%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.doi.org%2F10.1080%2F0023656032000057010%5C%22%3Ebecame%20hooked%3C%2Fa%3E%20on%20the%20idea%20of%20a%20flexible%2C%20temporary%20labor%20force%20that%20would%20not%20inflame%20anti-immigrant%20sentiment%20as%20much%20as%20more%20settled%20migrants%20seemingly%20did.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIsrael%E2%80%99s%20relationship%20with%20Thai%20workers%20came%20initially%20by%20way%20of%20the%20United%20States%E2%80%99%20support%20for%20the%201979%20peace%20agreement%20between%20Israel%20and%20Egypt.%20The%20U.S.%20government%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fusace.contentdm.oclc.org%2Fdigital%2Fcollection%2Fp16021coll4%2Fid%2F353%5C%22%3Erecruited%20Thai%20workers%3C%2Fa%3E%20who%20had%20once%20worked%20on%20Vietnam%20War-era%20U.S.%20military%20bases%20in%20northeastern%20Thailand%20to%20help%20build%20a%20new%20air%20force%20base%20in%20Israel.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20arrival%20of%20the%20Thai%20migrant%20workers%2C%20along%20with%20Portuguese%20workers%2C%20prompted%20public%20controversy%20among%20Israeli%20lawmakers%2C%20trade%20unionists%20and%20the%20media%20about%20the%20creation%20of%20a%20split%20labor%20market%2C%20as%20research%20done%20by%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fhu-berlin.academia.edu%2FSShoham%5C%22%3Eone%20of%20us%3C%2Fa%3E%20has%20shown.%20Meanwhile%2C%20others%20worried%20that%20the%20workers%E2%80%99%20presence%20cut%20against%20Zionist%20imperatives%20to%20guarantee%20a%20Jewish%20majority.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAttempting%20to%20resolve%20these%20contradictions%2C%20the%20Israeli%20government%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.trafflab.org%2Fshahar-shoham%5C%22%3Estarted%20to%20experiment%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20migration%20policies%20designed%20for%20a%20new%20category%20of%20workers%20%E2%80%93%20neither%20Jewish%20nor%20Palestinian%20%E2%80%93%20who%20were%20intended%20to%20remain%20separate%20from%20Israeli%20society.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20decade%20later%2C%20in%20a%20different%20political%20moment%2C%20these%20policy%20ideas%20would%20become%20concrete%20in%20a%20new%20category%20of%20person%20in%20Israel%3A%20the%20%E2%80%9C%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2Fabs%2F10.1111%2Fimre.12109%5C%22%3Eforeign%20worker%3C%2Fa%3E.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EGrowing%20recruitment%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Israeli-Palestinian%20conflict%20drove%20the%20%E2%80%9Cforeign%20worker%E2%80%9D%20policy%20forward.%20Though%20Israel%20was%20founded%20on%20the%20ideology%20of%20%E2%80%9Cavoda%20ivrit%2C%E2%80%9D%20or%20Hebrew%20labor%2C%20Israel%E2%80%99s%20occupation%20of%2